      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-acceptance-mrl3",
      "rationale": "The FEA solver (Abaqus 2023) is used under a validated and documented SQA plan conforming to FDA 21 CFR Part 820 QSR and ISO 13485. Version-controlled input decks are archived in a Git repository with audit trail. Regression test suite of 47 benchmark problems executed at each solver version update; all pass. SQA documentation package reviewed and approved by quality assurance lead. Achieved level 3 exceeds MRL 3 requirement of level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/code-verification-acceptance-mrl3",
      "rationale": "Abaqus 2023 has been verified against NAFEMS benchmarks LE1, LE3, and LE10 for linear elastic solid mechanics, and against patch test requirements for the C3D8R and C3D10 element formulations used in this model. Verification documentation is available in the Abaqus verification manual and has been independently confirmed by the simulation team against known analytical solutions for a thick-walled cylinder under internal pressure (error < 0.3%). Achieved level 2 meets MRL 3 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/discretization-error-acceptance-mrl3",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed per Roache (1994) GCI methodology (see ValidationResult vr003). Grid convergence index for peak von Mises stress is 1.8% and for peak micromotion is 2.3%, both below the pre-specified 5% acceptance criterion. Asymptotic convergence confirmed. The production mesh (1.25 mm nominal, 0.5 mm at stress concentrations) was selected as the balance between accuracy and computational cost. Achieved level 3 meets MRL 3 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-acceptance-mrl3",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted under ISO 14243-1 standardized loading conditions replicated in the FEA boundary conditions. Load magnitudes, waveform profiles, and fixture constraints were documented in the test protocol and independently verified by the test laboratory. Temperature (37 °C ± 0.5 °C), humidity, and specimen preparation procedures were controlled and recorded. Test conditions are directly traceable to the COU loading scenarios. Achieved level 3 exceeds MRL 3 requirement of level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-acceptance-mrl3",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison metrics defined a priori: mean absolute percentage error (MAPE) < 15% for stress and micromotion QoIs. Coupon stress validation achieved 4.2% MAPE; micromotion validation achieved 7.5% MAPE. Both within acceptance criterion. Uncertainty in experimental measurements (DIC strain uncertainty ±0.5%, LVDT uncertainty ±2 µm) was propagated and incorporated into comparison. Validation activities documented in vr001 and vr002. Achieved level 3 exceeds MRL 3 requirement of level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-acceptance-mrl3",
      "rationale": "The validation QoIs (von Mises stress in the tibial tray and bone-implant interface micromotion) are identical to the COU QoIs. Peak stress is directly compared against the UHMWPE and CoCr fatigue limits; peak micromotion is directly compared against the 150 µm osseointegration threshold. No surrogate quantities or indirect mappings are required. Achieved level 2 meets MRL 3 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-acceptance-mrl3",
      "rationale": "Validation activities were performed on composite sawbone tibial models (fourth-generation Sawbones, density matched to 50th-percentile male bone stock) under ISO 14243-1 loading, closely matching the COU patient population and loading environment. The implant geometry validated is the same design family as the COU device. Geometric and material differences between validation model and COU device are within the characterised uncertainty bounds. Domain coverage mapping confirms validation spans the full COU operating envelope. Achieved level 3 exceeds MRL 3 requirement of level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-acceptance-mrl3",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver convergence criterion set to residual norm < 1×10⁻⁸ for all load steps. Nonlinear contact iterations converge within 8 increments per step with no divergence or cutback warnings. Floating-point precision confirmed as double (64-bit) throughout. Solver error contribution to total numerical uncertainty estimated at < 0.1% via perturbation study, negligible relative to discretization error. Achieved level 2 meets MRL 3 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-acceptance-mrl3",
      "rationale": "Simulation workflow is documented in a controlled simulation plan (SP-TKR-2025-003) subject to independent peer review. Input deck preparation, boundary condition application, and post-processing scripts are version-controlled and reviewed by a second analyst before submission. A checklist-based QC review was completed prior to each production run. No use errors were identified during review. Achieved level 2 meets MRL 3 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-acceptance-mrl3",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic constitutive model is appropriate for the metallic tibial tray (CoCr alloy, strains < 0.1%) and validated against coupon data (vr001). Bone-implant contact modelled with Coulomb friction (µ = 0.4 ± 0.05) calibrated against published pull-out data. Bone stock represented as transversely isotropic elastic solid with density-modulus relationship from Morgan et al. (2003). Model form assumptions documented and justified in the simulation plan; sensitivity to friction coefficient and bone modulus evaluated in the Monte Carlo study (vr004). Achieved level 3 meets MRL 3 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-acceptance-mrl3",
      "rationale": "All material properties sourced from peer-reviewed literature and in-house coupon testing; distributions (mean ± SD) documented in the material properties dataset. Geometry derived from calibrated CT scans of the physical implant with dimensional verification against engineering drawings (tolerance ≤ 0.05 mm). Loading inputs taken from ISO 14243-1 with additional patient-variability envelope from Bergmann et al. (2001) instrumented implant data. Input uncertainty quantified and propagated via 500-sample Monte Carlo (vr004). Achieved level 3 meets MRL 3 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-samples-acceptance-mrl3",
      "rationale": "Six composite sawbone tibial specimens (three size 3, three size 5) used for micromotion validation; five cortical-bone-surrogate coupons used for stress validation. Sample sizes are consistent with ISO 14243-3 guidance for mechanical validation studies at this stage of development. Specimen-to-specimen variability characterised and incorporated into uncertainty quantification. Specimens are traceable to a single manufacturing lot with certificate of conformance. Achieved level 2 meets MRL 3 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/input-equivalency-acceptance-mrl3",
      "rationale": "A formal input-parameter equivalency assessment was performed comparing validation model inputs against COU model inputs across all material, geometric, and loading parameters. Maximum parameter deviation: bone modulus ±8% (within characterised population variability), friction coefficient ±12.5% (within sensitivity-studied range). All deviations are within the uncertainty bounds propagated in the Monte Carlo study. No extrapolation beyond the validated parameter space is required for the COU predictions. Achieved level 2 meets MRL 3 requirement."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-ortho-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for the tibial tray FEA model under COU1 is accepted at Model Risk Level 3. All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed; achieved credibility levels meet or exceed required levels for MRL 3 in every factor. Key evidence supporting acceptance: (1) Mesh convergence GCI values of 1.8% and 2.3% confirm numerical accuracy well within the 5% acceptance criterion; (2) Coupon stress validation (4.2% MAPE) and micromotion validation (7.5% MAPE) both meet the pre-specified 15% acceptance criterion; (3) Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation demonstrates 95th-percentile stress and micromotion remain below clinical thresholds with margins of 18% and 31% respectively; (4) Validation activities are directly relevant to the COU in terms of geometry, loading, and QoIs; (5) Software QA, use-error controls, and input documentation are compliant with FDA guidance and ISO 13485. No credibility factor gaps remain. The structured evidence base, complete provenance chain from raw experimental data through validated model outputs, and demonstrated uncertainty margins collectively support the conclusion that the FEA model is sufficiently credible to support the 510(k) substantial-equivalence submission for the Class II tibial tray device.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
